76561197996881287,Recommended,568930,35360639,Posted: 30 September,all,Harrison,"A remarkable game, doubly so given the one-person development team and small localization team. I urge any potentially intersted person to try the demo; it will give you an idea of the core gameplay and performance. Keep in mind the most interesting ideas and experiences are found in the main game.The Land of Pain provided a harrowing experience well worth the price. The developer has created wonderully tense and oppressive environments, where I could almost feel the weight of the surrounding darkness pressing in.  While the graphics are as pretty as you might expect from CryEngine, I was struck in particular with the stellar sound design; every creak, rustle, and squeak in the game seems perfectly placed to make me freeze in place out of fear.The story is engaging, with world-building that quickly moves in directions I doubt any would be able to predict, though it does adhere to a familiar Lovecraftian tradition. The monster is not a constant companion as in other games, but its presence is felt more accutely when  it appears, and the dread of it never truly went away as I played.The puzzles are not particularly complex, but are enjoyable and offer some challenge. They are helped by the fact that exploring the world is compelling on its own. The Land of Pain has game play, story, visuals, and audio to entertain for a few good hours, with a good price. I thoroughly enjoyed my time running, hiding, and exploring in it. The main character does walk kinda funny, though."
